		\begin<<726>>tex2html_deferred<<726>>\caption<<725>>GSM architecture\cite<<684>>GSMArchitectureProtocolsServices<<684>><<725>>\end<<727>>tex2html_deferred<<727>>
		\label<<685>>fig:GSMArchitecture<<685>>
	\end<<686>>centering<<686>>
\end<<687>>figure<<687>>
The \gls<<688>>MS<<688>> has the capability to change the transmission power it uses from 0.8, 2, 5, 8 MW to a maximum value of 20 MW\cite<<689>>GSMSysEngin<<689>>. The change in transmission power is automatically set to the lowest level by the \gls<<690>>BTS<<690>> to ensure reliable communication after evaluating the signal strength as measured by the \gls<<691>>MS<<691>> \cite<<692>>GSMSysEngin,GSMArchitectureProtocolsServices<<692>>. The power adjustment also minimises co-channel interference because the transmitted signal is less powerful and therefore less likely to interfere with other signals\cite<<693>>GSMSysEngin<<693>>. Co-channel interference is discussed in chapter~\ref<<694>>chpt:fap<<694>>
\begin<<728>>tex2html_deferred<<728>>\par\end<<729>>tex2html_deferred<<729>>
\subsection<<695>>Base Station Subsystem<<695>>
\begin<<730>>tex2html_deferred<<730>>\par\end<<731>>tex2html_deferred<<731>>
According to the \gls<<696>>gsm<<696>> Phase 2+ specification, this system is viewed by the \gls<<697>>MSC<<697>> through an Abis radio interface. The \gls<<698>>BSS<<698>> is responsible for communicating with mobile stations in a particular location area \cite<<699>>Eisenblatter<<699>>. The \gls<<700>>BSS<<700>> usually consists of one \gls<<701>>BSC<<701>> with one or more \glspl<<702>>BTS<<702>> that it controls \cite<<703>>Eisenblatter<<703>>.A \gls<<704>>BTS<<704>> has similar equipment to that of a MS\cite<<705>>GSMSysEngin<<705>>. Both have transceivers, antennae and the necessary functions to perform radio communication.
\begin<<732>>tex2html_deferred<<732>>\par\end<<733>>tex2html_deferred<<733>>
The communication link between the \gls<<706>>MSC<<706>> and \gls<<707>>BSC<<707>> is the called the A-interface. The interface between the \gls<<708>>BSC<<708>> and \gls<<709>>BTS<<709>> is called the Abis interface \cite<<710>>Eisenblatter<<710>>. The A and Abis interface as well as other interfaces between other \gls<<711>>gsm<<711>> architecture components are discussed in section~\ref<<712>>sec:gsminterfaces<<712>>.  
\begin<<734>>tex2html_deferred<<734>>\par\end<<735>>tex2html_deferred<<735>>
In a \gls<<713>>gsm<<713>> network a service area is defined as a geographical area where the networks wants to deliver its cellular network service to potential clients \cite<<714>>GSMArchitectureProtocolsServices, Karen2004<<714>>. The service area is subdivided into \glspl<<715>>LA<<715>> which are then further divided into smaller radio zones called cells \cite<<716>>GSMSecurInTeleNetwork<<716>>. When a cellular network is modelled, cells are modelled as hexagonal shapes. Each cell in the modelled network is served by only one \gls<<717>>BTS<<717>> and is usually regarded to be in the centre of a cell as can be seen in figure~\ref<<718>>fig:GSMCell<<718>>\cite<<719>>GSMArchitectureProtocolsServices<<719>>. 
